WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:11.240 --> 00:00:12.540
&gt;&gt; John Haskell:
Members of Congress

00:00:12.540 --> 00:00:15.430
and distinguished guests,
welcome, to the Library

00:00:15.430 --> 00:00:18.730
of Congress and the 8th
Henry A. Kissinger lecture.

00:00:18.730 --> 00:00:20.500
I'm John Haskell, director

00:00:20.500 --> 00:00:22.840
of the Kluge Center
here at the library.

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:26.180
The Kissinger program is made
possible by generous donations

00:00:26.180 --> 00:00:28.790
of the friends and
admirers of Dr. Kissinger

00:00:28.790 --> 00:00:32.410
who was the 56th Secretary
of State of the United States

00:00:32.410 --> 00:00:35.690
and a recipient of
the Nobel Peace Prize.

00:00:35.690 --> 00:00:39.210
Before we move on, on behalf
of all of us at the library,

00:00:39.210 --> 00:00:41.810
we join America in
mourning the passing

00:00:41.810 --> 00:00:45.150
of former president
George H.W. Bush.

00:00:45.150 --> 00:00:47.860
The Kissinger program
celebrates statesmanship

00:00:47.860 --> 00:00:51.330
and foreign policy, President
Bush's legacy of commitment

00:00:51.330 --> 00:00:53.420
to global diplomacy
is in keeping

00:00:53.420 --> 00:00:55.750
with exactly that tradition.

00:00:55.750 --> 00:00:58.010
We all wish the extended
Bush family

00:00:58.010 --> 00:01:02.550
and as many close friends the
best in this difficult time.

00:01:02.550 --> 00:01:05.260
In a similar vein, we mourn
the passing last month

00:01:05.260 --> 00:01:08.550
of Dr. James Billington, the
13th librarian of Congress.

00:01:08.550 --> 00:01:11.990
The Kissinger program is one
of his many legacies here

00:01:11.990 --> 00:01:13.970
at his distinguished
career at the library,

00:01:13.970 --> 00:01:15.970
which spanned 28 years.

00:01:15.970 --> 00:01:20.970
The Kissinger lecture has been
delivered by heads of state,

00:01:20.970 --> 00:01:24.110
including former Prime Minister
Tony Blair, former president

00:01:24.110 --> 00:01:27.540
of Mexico, Filipe Calderon,
former president of Brazil,

00:01:27.540 --> 00:01:30.800
Fernando Enrique
Cardoso, former president

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:33.480
of the French Republic
Valery Giscard d'Estaing,

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:37.100
as well as former United
States Secretaries of State,

00:01:37.100 --> 00:01:40.650
James Baker, George Schultz,
and Dr. Kissinger, himself.

00:01:40.650 --> 00:01:44.660
As is customary, tonight's
program will include an address

00:01:44.660 --> 00:01:48.400
by our Kissinger lecturer,
Madame Christine Lagarde,

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:51.600
followed by a conversation
with Margaret Brennan,

00:01:51.600 --> 00:01:54.870
CBS News senior foreign
affairs correspondent and host

00:01:54.870 --> 00:01:56.700
of Face of the Nation.

00:01:56.700 --> 00:01:59.180
At this time, it is
my distinct pleasure

00:01:59.180 --> 00:02:03.510
to introduce Dr. Carla Hayden,
the 14th librarian of Congress.

00:02:03.510 --> 00:02:13.190
[ Applause ]

00:02:13.190 --> 00:02:15.100
&gt;&gt; Dr. Carla Hayden: Good
evening, Madame Lagarde,

00:02:15.100 --> 00:02:18.760
members of Congress, and
distinguished guests.

00:02:18.760 --> 00:02:21.860
We are deeply honored to
welcome to the Library

00:02:21.860 --> 00:02:26.100
of Congress tonight Christine
Lagarde, managing director

00:02:26.100 --> 00:02:29.290
of the International
Monetary Fund.

00:02:30.450 --> 00:02:33.320
As you can see, we
are in the great hall

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:35.810
of the library's Thomas
Jefferson building,

00:02:35.810 --> 00:02:40.340
surrounded by visual art,
symbolizing the progress

00:02:40.340 --> 00:02:43.140
of civilization and the
traditions of knowledge

00:02:43.140 --> 00:02:46.290
and learning, a most
fitting venue

00:02:46.290 --> 00:02:49.720
for the 8th Kissinger lecture.

00:02:49.720 --> 00:02:53.860
Madame Christine Lagarde is a
distinguished public servant

00:02:53.860 --> 00:02:56.390
with deep knowledge of
the world's economy,

00:02:56.390 --> 00:02:59.590
and the ways financial
architecture can shape the lives

00:02:59.590 --> 00:03:03.730
of individuals in
countries around the globe.

00:03:03.730 --> 00:03:08.120
Among her many other high
ranking points and posts

00:03:08.120 --> 00:03:12.100
in government and the
private sector, in June 2007,

00:03:12.100 --> 00:03:15.880
she became the first woman
to hold the post of finance

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:19.550
and economy minister
of a G7 country.

00:03:19.550 --> 00:03:21.880
Later, as chairman of the G20,

00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:26.060
she set in motion a wide
ranging agenda on the reform

00:03:26.060 --> 00:03:29.180
of international
monetary systems.

00:03:29.180 --> 00:03:32.150
And on July 5th, 2011,

00:03:32.150 --> 00:03:36.450
Ms. Lagarde became the 11th
managing director of the IMF

00:03:36.450 --> 00:03:39.170
and the first woman
to hold that position.

00:03:39.170 --> 00:03:45.450
And on February 19th, 2016, the
IMF executive board selected her

00:03:45.450 --> 00:03:51.750
to serve as managing director
for a second five year term.

00:03:51.750 --> 00:03:55.250
She has tackled some of the most
challenging financial issues

00:03:55.250 --> 00:04:00.970
related to European integration,
international trade,

00:04:00.970 --> 00:04:05.950
and the development of
global economic governance.

00:04:05.950 --> 00:04:09.900
However, I am excited
to be the person

00:04:09.900 --> 00:04:13.970
that will deliver breaking news.

00:04:16.370 --> 00:04:19.710
The room just got
a little quieter.

00:04:19.710 --> 00:04:21.390
[Laughter].

00:04:21.390 --> 00:04:29.620
Well, today, Forbes released
its 100 Most Powerful Women

00:04:29.620 --> 00:04:34.640
in the World and Madame
Christine Lagarde was voted the

00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:39.510
third most powerful
woman in the world.

00:04:39.510 --> 00:04:45.920
[ Applause ]

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:48.330
So ladies and gentleman,
please join me

00:04:48.330 --> 00:04:51.510
in welcoming Ms.
Christine Lagarde.

00:04:51.510 --> 00:05:09.720
[ Applause ]

00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:11.940
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Thank
you, very much, Dr. Hayden,

00:05:11.940 --> 00:05:16.180
dear Carla, for this generous
and brief introduction.

00:05:16.180 --> 00:05:17.970
They are the best.

00:05:17.970 --> 00:05:20.480
They are the best.

00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:23.820
I'm so happy to see many
of you here, my friends,

00:05:23.820 --> 00:05:28.200
and very much looking forward to
the discussion that we will have

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:31.370
after these remarks
with Margaret Brennan.

00:05:31.370 --> 00:05:34.800
And thank you also, Mr.
Haskell, for the warm welcome

00:05:34.800 --> 00:05:39.200
that you've extended
to all of us.

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:43.070
He could not be here tonight
but I had a conversation

00:05:43.070 --> 00:05:47.230
with him just before arriving
at this beautiful Library

00:05:47.230 --> 00:05:50.360
of Congress and Henry
Kissinger was delighted

00:05:50.360 --> 00:05:53.960
that we were gathering tonight
and he has asked me to express

00:05:53.960 --> 00:05:58.920
to all of you his best wishes
and very strong support

00:05:58.920 --> 00:06:02.970
for continuing the lecture
that he started back in 2001.

00:06:05.280 --> 00:06:09.020
I would also like
to indicate myself

00:06:09.020 --> 00:06:12.070
that somebody else is very
much in our thoughts tonight.

00:06:12.070 --> 00:06:16.070
And that is, obviously, former
President George H.W. Bush

00:06:16.070 --> 00:06:19.060
and all his family members.

00:06:19.060 --> 00:06:23.010
We all mourn his passing, many
others are trying to enter

00:06:23.010 --> 00:06:25.670
into the rotunda as we speak.

00:06:25.670 --> 00:06:30.910
And we celebrate
the arc of his life.

00:06:30.910 --> 00:06:34.700
The pilot who bravely fought
in World War II, the president

00:06:34.700 --> 00:06:38.950
who helped heal division after
the cold war, and the statesman

00:06:38.950 --> 00:06:44.060
who believed in the power of
international cooperation.

00:06:44.060 --> 00:06:46.600
I hope to honor his
spirit tonight.

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:49.970
And I was privileged
to meet him recently

00:06:49.970 --> 00:06:52.860
on several occasions
up in Maine.

00:06:52.860 --> 00:06:54.990
And I could appreciate
what a kind,

00:06:54.990 --> 00:06:58.940
generous, and noble man he was.

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:04.740
So tonight -- tonight
is December 4th.

00:07:04.740 --> 00:07:11.160
It's actually an important
date for a particularly reason

00:07:11.160 --> 00:07:13.110
that I will not mention
to you now.

00:07:13.110 --> 00:07:15.230
You'll have to wait until
the end of my remarks.

00:07:15.230 --> 00:07:16.530
[Laughter].

00:07:16.530 --> 00:07:20.220
And you're not allowed to look
at your cell phone, please.

00:07:20.220 --> 00:07:21.520
[Laughter].

00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:26.890
No. I have to confess
something here.

00:07:26.890 --> 00:07:29.390
When I walked into
the great hall

00:07:29.390 --> 00:07:36.090
and was given a lovely private
tour by you, Dr. Hayden,

00:07:36.090 --> 00:07:41.590
three thoughts crossed my mind.

00:07:41.590 --> 00:07:50.070
The first one was, this young
French student who was studying

00:07:50.070 --> 00:07:55.020
for her political science
dissertation back 42 years ago,

00:07:55.020 --> 00:08:00.720
and has spent quite a little bit
of time, in the reading room,

00:08:00.720 --> 00:08:02.810
thanks to the courtesy of
the Library of Congress,

00:08:02.810 --> 00:08:05.910
I was able to better
research the work that I did

00:08:05.910 --> 00:08:10.490
on Ralph Nader and the American
consumerism of those days.

00:08:10.490 --> 00:08:11.790
Thank you.

00:08:11.790 --> 00:08:13.720
I am in your debt.

00:08:13.720 --> 00:08:16.330
The second person whom I
thought about was my son,

00:08:16.330 --> 00:08:18.160
who is a young architect.

00:08:18.160 --> 00:08:21.120
He would love this place.

00:08:21.120 --> 00:08:22.930
He would love it.

00:08:22.930 --> 00:08:26.930
The space, the height,
the creativity.

00:08:26.930 --> 00:08:32.300
And the third thought I had
was about my country, France.

00:08:32.300 --> 00:08:33.900
And maybe another
country, actually,

00:08:33.900 --> 00:08:37.850
that I was just visiting a
couple of days, Argentina.

00:08:37.850 --> 00:08:41.000
Now why is that?

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:49.460
Well, when this structure
was completed in 1897,

00:08:49.460 --> 00:08:55.860
the chief engineer remarked, I
quote, "that the Palais Garnier,

00:08:55.860 --> 00:08:59.910
the Paris Opera House,
was the prime suggestion

00:08:59.910 --> 00:09:03.440
for the new Library
of Congress."

00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:05.170
That makes sense, actually.

00:09:05.170 --> 00:09:10.070
Because the Paris Opera House
was completed 20 years earlier

00:09:10.070 --> 00:09:11.750
in 1875.

00:09:11.750 --> 00:09:17.060
Now, I think the French may
have borrowed a little bit

00:09:17.060 --> 00:09:18.360
from others.

00:09:18.360 --> 00:09:21.630
Because the Teatro Colón
in Buenos Aires was,

00:09:21.630 --> 00:09:24.750
itself, finished in 1857.

00:09:24.750 --> 00:09:28.410
And if you look at these
three buildings, well,

00:09:28.410 --> 00:09:30.630
it tells you something.

00:09:30.630 --> 00:09:34.750
First of all, that valuable
intellectual property was

00:09:34.750 --> 00:09:38.990
of great interest across
borders, even back then,

00:09:38.990 --> 00:09:43.080
at least among architects
who happily borrowed

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:45.820
from each other,
learned from each other,

00:09:45.820 --> 00:09:48.740
became inspired as a result.

00:09:48.740 --> 00:09:53.010
Second, it reminds us
that they understood

00:09:53.010 --> 00:09:58.310
that building something
lasting means linking the solid

00:09:58.310 --> 00:10:02.340
foundations of the past with
the spark of imagination.

00:10:02.340 --> 00:10:06.010
You can't just copycat.

00:10:06.010 --> 00:10:09.720
That kind of creativity
and long-term vision rooted

00:10:09.720 --> 00:10:13.440
in history and informed by
our successes and failures

00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:16.610
from the past is my
theme for this evening.

00:10:16.610 --> 00:10:20.480
First, where have we been?

00:10:20.480 --> 00:10:22.240
How has creativity

00:10:22.240 --> 00:10:27.010
and international economy
cooperation helped bring more

00:10:27.010 --> 00:10:31.310
prosperity and more
peace in the world?

00:10:31.310 --> 00:10:35.300
And second, where can
we travel together?

00:10:35.300 --> 00:10:39.660
How can creativity and informed
visionary thinking help adapt

00:10:39.660 --> 00:10:44.740
the international system
to our current challenges?

00:10:44.740 --> 00:10:48.730
So let me begin first with a
little bit of shared history

00:10:48.730 --> 00:10:51.070
between the international
monetary fund

00:10:51.070 --> 00:10:54.970
and the United States
over the last 75 years.

00:10:58.160 --> 00:11:01.750
In the first half
of the 20th century,

00:11:01.750 --> 00:11:06.340
the dominant economy [inaudible]
military powers used force

00:11:06.340 --> 00:11:10.440
to assert their self-interests
at enormous costs in terms

00:11:10.440 --> 00:11:14.450
of human life and
physical destruction.

00:11:14.450 --> 00:11:18.590
The tragic results compelled
nations to find a better way.

00:11:18.590 --> 00:11:23.580
It only took them two wars
and atrocities along the way.

00:11:23.580 --> 00:11:28.710
But in 1944, they found it.

00:11:28.710 --> 00:11:33.740
The United States emerged
as the major global power

00:11:33.740 --> 00:11:36.310
and did something unprecedented.

00:11:36.310 --> 00:11:40.800
Informed by the devastating,
ultimate outcome

00:11:40.800 --> 00:11:44.190
of the Versailles Treaty
at the end of World War I,

00:11:44.190 --> 00:11:48.640
for which we just celebrated
the 100-anniversary,

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:52.060
the United States
decided to use its power

00:11:52.060 --> 00:11:55.310
in the service of cooperation.

00:11:55.310 --> 00:12:00.290
It was an experiment that
would shape our modern world.

00:12:00.290 --> 00:12:04.060
And in his inaugural
lecture in 2001,

00:12:04.060 --> 00:12:06.090
Dr. Kissinger called
the innovations

00:12:06.090 --> 00:12:11.950
of the post war period, I quote,
"a great burst of creativity

00:12:11.950 --> 00:12:14.020
that brought security
to the world."

00:12:14.020 --> 00:12:18.580
How did the U.S. do it?

00:12:18.580 --> 00:12:20.630
Out of generosity?

00:12:20.630 --> 00:12:24.880
Yes. With consideration
to their self interests?

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:30.960
Yes. And with a little help
from some of their friends.

00:12:30.960 --> 00:12:36.660
Let us look at that turning
point of 75 years ago

00:12:36.660 --> 00:12:38.260
and think first of the creation

00:12:38.260 --> 00:12:40.590
of the Breton Wood
system, itself.

00:12:40.590 --> 00:12:46.310
The principle architects,
John Maynard Keynes of the U.K

00:12:46.310 --> 00:12:50.220
and Harry Dexter White of the
U.S. were deeply influenced

00:12:50.220 --> 00:12:52.870
by the period between
the two wars.

00:12:52.870 --> 00:12:56.640
They witnessed a
moment in history

00:12:56.640 --> 00:13:00.020
when flawed domestic policies
poisoned international

00:13:00.020 --> 00:13:03.670
relationships, which
themselves were built

00:13:03.670 --> 00:13:05.450
on troubled foundations.

00:13:05.450 --> 00:13:08.310
Treaty of Versailles.

00:13:08.310 --> 00:13:11.390
The result was protectionism

00:13:11.390 --> 00:13:14.820
and competitive currency
devaluations,

00:13:14.820 --> 00:13:18.600
imploding world trade
deepened the Great Depression

00:13:18.600 --> 00:13:23.530
and caused massive economic,
financial, and social upheaval.

00:13:23.530 --> 00:13:27.270
Ultimately, these pressures
gave rise to nationalist

00:13:27.270 --> 00:13:31.220
and populist movements and
eventually catastrophe.

00:13:33.110 --> 00:13:36.750
Emerging from the second
world war, the U.S.

00:13:36.750 --> 00:13:40.380
and some other 40 countries
gathered in Bretton Woods,

00:13:40.380 --> 00:13:42.690
New Hampshire, and decided

00:13:42.690 --> 00:13:45.590
to create the International
Monetary Fund

00:13:45.590 --> 00:13:47.580
and the World Bank.

00:13:47.580 --> 00:13:52.370
They tasked the fund with
three critical missions,

00:13:52.370 --> 00:13:55.920
promoting international
monetary cooperation,

00:13:55.920 --> 00:14:00.250
supporting the expansion of
trade and economic growth,

00:14:00.250 --> 00:14:04.430
and discouraging policies
that would harm prosperity.

00:14:04.430 --> 00:14:08.520
It was revolutionary.

00:14:08.520 --> 00:14:10.070
It was visionary.

00:14:10.070 --> 00:14:11.370
And guess what?

00:14:11.370 --> 00:14:12.670
It worked.

00:14:12.670 --> 00:14:19.250
From the very beginning, the IMF
held countries address major new

00:14:19.250 --> 00:14:23.210
challenges through
collaboration.

00:14:23.210 --> 00:14:26.370
Complimenting the marshal plan,

00:14:26.370 --> 00:14:30.810
we at the IMF helped Europe
rebuild from the rubble of war.

00:14:30.810 --> 00:14:33.850
Our loans gave countries
breathing space

00:14:33.850 --> 00:14:36.300
to stabilize their
economies in difficult time

00:14:36.300 --> 00:14:40.700
and implement policies
to promote growth.

00:14:40.700 --> 00:14:43.890
It's a mission that we
continue to this day,

00:14:43.890 --> 00:14:48.380
as you may have recently seen in
countries like Argentina, Egypt,

00:14:48.380 --> 00:14:51.250
Ukraine and many others.

00:14:51.250 --> 00:14:55.120
The genius of the collaborative
system that they invented was

00:14:55.120 --> 00:14:59.430
that it was designed
to adapt and change.

00:14:59.430 --> 00:15:07.410
And in the early '70s,
that change arrived.

00:15:07.410 --> 00:15:11.170
Some of you might remember
that speech, a landmark speech.

00:15:11.170 --> 00:15:13.440
The challenge of peace.

00:15:13.440 --> 00:15:16.700
President Nixon suspended the
U.S. dollars convertibility

00:15:16.700 --> 00:15:18.000
into gold.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.870
And that decision
shocked the world

00:15:20.870 --> 00:15:25.490
and forced a year-long
negotiation that led

00:15:25.490 --> 00:15:30.480
to the modern floating
exchange rate structure,

00:15:30.480 --> 00:15:36.790
away from the fixed gold
reference structure moving

00:15:36.790 --> 00:15:38.790
into floating exchange
rate structure.

00:15:38.790 --> 00:15:41.950
A system that is
still today in place

00:15:41.950 --> 00:15:45.010
in many corners of the world.

00:15:45.010 --> 00:15:47.200
But at the time, some thought

00:15:47.200 --> 00:15:52.310
that this particular change
would mean the end of the IMF.

00:15:52.310 --> 00:15:56.230
But all our members at the time,
including the United States knew

00:15:56.230 --> 00:15:57.530
that the goal of stability

00:15:57.530 --> 00:16:01.940
and prosperity extended well
beyond fixed exchange rates.

00:16:01.940 --> 00:16:03.250
They recognized the benefits

00:16:03.250 --> 00:16:06.850
of a global financial
[inaudible] fighter

00:16:06.850 --> 00:16:10.830
that could help countries
in times of need.

00:16:10.830 --> 00:16:12.880
They built on what worked,

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:15.870
changed what did not,
and they adapted.

00:16:15.870 --> 00:16:22.600
And we moved on,
1973, the oil crisis.

00:16:22.600 --> 00:16:24.870
The IMF created new tools

00:16:24.870 --> 00:16:28.280
to help countries facing
an energy emergency in line

00:16:28.280 --> 00:16:31.210
with the funds role
to help smooth shocks

00:16:31.210 --> 00:16:34.370
and prevent harmful spillovers.

00:16:34.370 --> 00:16:39.700
As a debt crisis hit lots
in America in the '80s,

00:16:39.700 --> 00:16:42.090
the IMF with creative
ideas and support

00:16:42.090 --> 00:16:45.990
from the United States
stepped in to calm the waters.

00:16:45.990 --> 00:16:48.230
And after the fall
of the Berlin Wall,

00:16:48.230 --> 00:16:49.880
we took on a new challenge,

00:16:49.880 --> 00:16:54.290
which was helping the former
Soviet Union block nations

00:16:54.290 --> 00:16:57.630
transform themselves
from centrally planned

00:16:57.630 --> 00:17:00.310
to free market economies.

00:17:00.310 --> 00:17:03.240
In the 1990s, the fund
assisted countries

00:17:03.240 --> 00:17:07.030
in overcoming first
the Mexican peso crisis

00:17:07.030 --> 00:17:10.220
and then the Asian
financial crisis.

00:17:10.220 --> 00:17:12.660
And throughout all
these challenges,

00:17:12.660 --> 00:17:14.820
we continue to help
countries around the world

00:17:14.820 --> 00:17:17.120
with the economic fundamentals.

00:17:17.120 --> 00:17:20.400
Their fiscal, monetary,
and exchange rate policies

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:24.270
and with steps to build
stronger economic institutions.

00:17:24.270 --> 00:17:28.670
Because without that
macroeconomic stability growth

00:17:28.670 --> 00:17:30.990
cannot prosper.

00:17:30.990 --> 00:17:36.060
These efforts enabled better
policies that opened markets,

00:17:36.060 --> 00:17:38.910
bolstered trade, created jobs,

00:17:38.910 --> 00:17:41.300
and unleashed economic
potential.

00:17:41.300 --> 00:17:48.270
And then came 2008 and
the financial crisis,

00:17:48.270 --> 00:17:50.590
the global financial crisis.

00:17:50.590 --> 00:17:56.460
Most of the other crisis that
I have referred to applied

00:17:56.460 --> 00:17:58.020
to particular regions.

00:17:58.020 --> 00:18:02.110
This one was the first of
a completely global nature.

00:18:02.110 --> 00:18:04.850
The ensuing great
recession reminded us

00:18:04.850 --> 00:18:09.060
that international cooperation
was essential not optional

00:18:09.060 --> 00:18:11.500
and as the French finance
minister at the time,

00:18:11.500 --> 00:18:14.730
I certainly was [inaudible]
in that exercise.

00:18:14.730 --> 00:18:20.900
All G20 nations and the Federal
Reserve took extraordinary steps

00:18:20.900 --> 00:18:23.480
to save the system.

00:18:23.480 --> 00:18:28.240
As veterans when we
sort of come together,

00:18:28.240 --> 00:18:30.760
we just wonder how we did it?

00:18:30.760 --> 00:18:36.290
And how much we transgressed and
had to violate many principles

00:18:36.290 --> 00:18:39.640
and rules and just reinvent.

00:18:39.640 --> 00:18:43.590
But at the time, the IMF
deployed its own fire power

00:18:43.590 --> 00:18:49.140
committing over $500 billion to
help secure the global economy.

00:18:49.140 --> 00:18:53.720
And in the decade since
the 2008 financial crisis,

00:18:53.720 --> 00:18:59.120
we supported economic
programs in 90 countries

00:18:59.120 --> 00:19:01.200
and adopted our lending
instruments,

00:19:01.200 --> 00:19:05.970
including zero interest loans,
to help low-income countries.

00:19:07.050 --> 00:19:11.260
But the global economy did
not only need liquidity

00:19:11.260 --> 00:19:12.930
and stimulus, it also needed

00:19:12.930 --> 00:19:16.100
to reform its financial
architecture.

00:19:16.100 --> 00:19:17.970
And we worked with
our membership

00:19:17.970 --> 00:19:21.150
to build a stronger
financial sector

00:19:21.150 --> 00:19:24.690
so that we could together
limit the consequences

00:19:24.690 --> 00:19:27.670
of what will be one
day the next crisis.

00:19:27.670 --> 00:19:29.960
So we learned from the past.

00:19:29.960 --> 00:19:35.080
We got creative and we
changed for the better.

00:19:35.080 --> 00:19:37.810
And none of that -- none of
that would have been possible

00:19:37.810 --> 00:19:40.090
without the United States.

00:19:40.090 --> 00:19:43.110
This country challenged the
international economy corridor

00:19:43.110 --> 00:19:44.820
when it needed challenging.

00:19:44.820 --> 00:19:48.700
It forged compromise when
compromise was necessary.

00:19:48.700 --> 00:19:52.320
Why? Why did it do all that?

00:19:52.320 --> 00:19:53.830
Benevolence?

00:19:53.830 --> 00:19:56.670
It does so because a stronger

00:19:56.670 --> 00:20:02.160
and more stable world paid
dividends for the United States.

00:20:02.160 --> 00:20:06.630
It enabled the U.S. to enjoy
some of the longest runs

00:20:06.630 --> 00:20:11.570
of sustained economic growth
the modern world has ever known.

00:20:11.570 --> 00:20:17.890
Since that meeting at Bretton
Woods nearly 75 years ago real

00:20:17.890 --> 00:20:22.850
U.S. GDP increased
by a factor of eight.

00:20:22.850 --> 00:20:27.650
And the average Americans
real income has quadrupled.

00:20:27.650 --> 00:20:33.260
And this success did not come
at the expense of other nations.

00:20:33.260 --> 00:20:36.810
On the contrary, this country's
collaborative leadership paved

00:20:36.810 --> 00:20:41.260
the way, not only for decades
of opportunities here in America

00:20:41.260 --> 00:20:44.970
but also for growth that
spread across the world.

00:20:48.040 --> 00:20:53.600
Now, today that landscape
is shifting again.

00:20:53.600 --> 00:20:58.940
And part of this change
is driven by geopolitics

00:20:58.940 --> 00:21:03.460
and the shift in some economic
power from west to east.

00:21:03.460 --> 00:21:04.760
Part of it by the rise

00:21:04.760 --> 00:21:09.990
of non state actors including
multi-national organizations

00:21:09.990 --> 00:21:11.630
and corporates.

00:21:11.630 --> 00:21:15.620
Part of it is driven
by technology

00:21:15.620 --> 00:21:21.420
and the rapid acceleration
of everything in our lives.

00:21:21.420 --> 00:21:24.820
As I'm sure you know,
Dr. Hayden,

00:21:24.820 --> 00:21:28.430
90 percent of the world's
data was created just

00:21:28.430 --> 00:21:30.850
over the last two years.

00:21:30.850 --> 00:21:36.100
Now, I have to say as a daughter
of two classics professors,

00:21:36.100 --> 00:21:37.810
I know my parents
would have found

00:21:37.810 --> 00:21:39.370
that very, very depressing.

00:21:39.370 --> 00:21:41.290
[Laughter].

00:21:41.290 --> 00:21:47.150
But the truth is that everything
moves faster, information,

00:21:47.150 --> 00:21:49.570
money, disease, you name it.

00:21:49.570 --> 00:21:53.370
And this transformation can
bring enormous opportunities

00:21:53.370 --> 00:21:55.770
but they can also
create massive risks.

00:21:55.770 --> 00:21:58.750
Why is that?

00:21:58.750 --> 00:22:03.750
Because more than every before
at least as was demonstrated

00:22:03.750 --> 00:22:10.260
in 2008, what happens one nation
is going to impact all nations.

00:22:10.260 --> 00:22:14.080
From weapons of mass
destruction to cybersecurity

00:22:14.080 --> 00:22:16.410
to the interconnected
financial system,

00:22:16.410 --> 00:22:21.000
many of our current
challenges recognize no borders.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:22.800
So when support

00:22:22.800 --> 00:22:26.150
for international
cooperation falters,

00:22:26.150 --> 00:22:29.440
we must remember the
lessons the United States

00:22:29.440 --> 00:22:33.680
and her allies taught the
world over the last 75 years.

00:22:33.680 --> 00:22:36.950
It's a big lesson.

00:22:36.950 --> 00:22:40.050
Solidarity is self interest.

00:22:40.050 --> 00:22:46.510
And that principle endures
in our changing world.

00:22:46.510 --> 00:22:52.040
Our challenge now is to
yet again adapt and reform.

00:22:52.040 --> 00:22:57.450
So I believe that
this year, 2019,

00:22:57.450 --> 00:23:00.220
can be another turning
point in our journey.

00:23:00.220 --> 00:23:03.810
A moment when the world delivers
a new burst of creativity

00:23:03.810 --> 00:23:07.130
in solving our shared
challenges.

00:23:07.130 --> 00:23:09.300
Actually there's something
up there that you can't see

00:23:09.300 --> 00:23:12.550
but from which we
can draw inspiration.

00:23:12.550 --> 00:23:13.860
Correct me if I'm wrong.

00:23:13.860 --> 00:23:17.650
But it's something like,
they build too low those

00:23:17.650 --> 00:23:21.130
who build beneath the stars.

00:23:21.130 --> 00:23:24.800
It's written up there.

00:23:24.800 --> 00:23:28.510
Imagine what the world
could be if we were

00:23:28.510 --> 00:23:32.270
to build beneath the
stars, the [inaudible],

00:23:32.270 --> 00:23:36.120
as I call it, or
the age of anger.

00:23:36.120 --> 00:23:40.940
Let's imagine the age of anger.

00:23:40.940 --> 00:23:47.990
By 2040, inequality could exceed
the levels of the gilded age.

00:23:47.990 --> 00:23:50.680
Strong tech monopolice
and weak governments

00:23:50.680 --> 00:23:53.330
with ineffective domestic
policies could make it

00:23:53.330 --> 00:23:57.110
impossible for start ups and
entrepreneurs to succeed.

00:23:57.110 --> 00:24:03.330
Health breakthroughs could allow
the richest to live past 120,

00:24:03.330 --> 00:24:05.400
while millions of
others would suffer

00:24:05.400 --> 00:24:08.280
from extreme poverty
and disease.

00:24:08.280 --> 00:24:12.140
Social media would bombard
the left behind population

00:24:12.140 --> 00:24:15.930
and [inaudible] the disparity
between their reality

00:24:15.930 --> 00:24:17.750
and the possibility
of a better life

00:24:17.750 --> 00:24:23.910
and the aspiration gap would
fuel resentment and anger.

00:24:23.910 --> 00:24:26.840
Trust between nations
would break down.

00:24:26.840 --> 00:24:29.960
The world would be more
interconnected digitally

00:24:29.960 --> 00:24:33.060
but less connected
in every other way.

00:24:33.060 --> 00:24:35.880
International cooperation
for the benefit

00:24:35.880 --> 00:24:39.840
of all would be a concept
best studied in libraries,

00:24:39.840 --> 00:24:44.790
like this one, but rarely
practiced on the world stage due

00:24:44.790 --> 00:24:47.250
to the supremacy of
national interest

00:24:47.250 --> 00:24:50.220
and a singular focus
on domestic policies.

00:24:50.220 --> 00:24:55.200
To borrow from Dr. Kissinger's
world order we might be,

00:24:55.200 --> 00:24:57.750
I quote, "facing a period

00:24:57.750 --> 00:25:00.020
in which forces beyond
the restraints

00:25:00.020 --> 00:25:02.920
of any order determine
the future."

00:25:04.190 --> 00:25:07.300
That is a very dystopian
scenario.

00:25:07.300 --> 00:25:13.280
Isn't it? Not one that we
designed and certainly not one

00:25:13.280 --> 00:25:16.180
that I believe can, and
should be, our destiny.

00:25:16.180 --> 00:25:19.810
Neither does Dr.
Kissinger, for that matter.

00:25:19.810 --> 00:25:23.220
We have overcome
existential threats before

00:25:23.220 --> 00:25:25.290
and we can do so again.

00:25:25.290 --> 00:25:27.960
Think of the world.

00:25:27.960 --> 00:25:32.810
If we make 2019 the start
of a different kind of A-I.

00:25:32.810 --> 00:25:36.530
Everybody thinks, oh,
she's going to talk

00:25:36.530 --> 00:25:38.400
about artificial intelligence.

00:25:38.400 --> 00:25:42.970
No. Age of ingenuity.

00:25:45.190 --> 00:25:51.100
This would be a future fueled
by creativity and cooperation.

00:25:51.100 --> 00:25:54.490
Okay, 2040.

00:25:54.490 --> 00:25:57.670
I'm in a new scenario now.

00:25:57.670 --> 00:26:00.900
We would see flourishing
economies predominantly running

00:26:00.900 --> 00:26:02.840
on renewable energy.

00:26:02.840 --> 00:26:06.170
Women would be fully empowered
in the workforce proving

00:26:06.170 --> 00:26:08.950
to be an economic and
social game changer.

00:26:08.950 --> 00:26:10.250
New pension systems

00:26:10.250 --> 00:26:13.800
and healthcare portability would
reflect the changing nature

00:26:13.800 --> 00:26:16.500
of work in the digital economy.

00:26:16.500 --> 00:26:20.060
Corporation would embrace
social responsibility as part

00:26:20.060 --> 00:26:23.020
of their business model
because they would be rated

00:26:23.020 --> 00:26:24.850
on that basis as well.

00:26:24.850 --> 00:26:27.770
Technology called
wizardry could save lives

00:26:27.770 --> 00:26:30.280
and create millions of jobs.

00:26:30.280 --> 00:26:33.920
We would see an end to mass
migration, trade would expand

00:26:33.920 --> 00:26:36.540
across the world and
peaceful coexistence

00:26:36.540 --> 00:26:39.700
between nations would prevail.

00:26:39.700 --> 00:26:42.120
Am I being too optimistic?

00:26:42.120 --> 00:26:44.430
Of course.

00:26:44.430 --> 00:26:48.730
You know the difference between
the optimist and the pessimist?

00:26:48.730 --> 00:26:51.990
They're both wrong but
the optimist is happier.

00:26:51.990 --> 00:26:53.700
[Laughter].

00:26:53.700 --> 00:26:56.820
So I have to be optimistic.

00:26:56.820 --> 00:26:59.700
Because I'm thinking about the
world my grown children will

00:26:59.700 --> 00:27:01.420
enter it.

00:27:01.420 --> 00:27:07.870
But it presents us with a
fundamental choice, stand still

00:27:07.870 --> 00:27:11.940
and watch discord and discontent
bubble over into conflict.

00:27:11.940 --> 00:27:17.900
Or, move forward, reimagine
the way nations work together

00:27:17.900 --> 00:27:22.490
and build prosperity and peace.

00:27:22.490 --> 00:27:23.800
Okay, nice words.

00:27:23.800 --> 00:27:25.170
What does it mean in practice?

00:27:25.170 --> 00:27:30.200
It means countries working
together to put people,

00:27:30.200 --> 00:27:33.730
all people, at the
center of all our efforts.

00:27:33.730 --> 00:27:37.770
Focusing on real results
to improve their lives.

00:27:37.770 --> 00:27:39.070
It also means governments

00:27:39.070 --> 00:27:42.390
and institutions being more
transparent and accountable,

00:27:42.390 --> 00:27:46.590
which includes listening
to more diverse voices.

00:27:46.590 --> 00:27:48.690
It means ensuring
that economic benefits

00:27:48.690 --> 00:27:55.350
of globalizations are shared
by many, not just a few.

00:27:55.350 --> 00:27:57.260
I call that the new
multilateralism

00:27:57.260 --> 00:27:58.560
[assumed spelling].

00:27:58.560 --> 00:27:59.860
You might just call
it common sense,

00:27:59.860 --> 00:28:03.700
if that word suits you better.

00:28:03.700 --> 00:28:06.870
But let me be very clear here.

00:28:06.870 --> 00:28:10.620
Good international cooperation
is never going to substitute

00:28:10.620 --> 00:28:12.070
for good domestic policy.

00:28:12.070 --> 00:28:15.440
And of course, individual
countries have the

00:28:15.440 --> 00:28:19.240
responsibility for the well
being of their citizens.

00:28:19.240 --> 00:28:23.080
In fact, strong domestic
policies can form the foundation

00:28:23.080 --> 00:28:25.340
for effective international
cooperation

00:28:25.340 --> 00:28:29.820
and in our modern world,
there are some issues

00:28:29.820 --> 00:28:31.940
that can only be addressed

00:28:31.940 --> 00:28:34.170
through international
cooperation.

00:28:34.170 --> 00:28:38.580
I want to discuss
four such issues.

00:28:38.580 --> 00:28:41.300
I promise I'll be brief
on each of the four.

00:28:41.300 --> 00:28:43.400
But I think they're
all important.

00:28:43.400 --> 00:28:49.440
And to be successful in
delivering on those four,

00:28:49.440 --> 00:28:54.200
we will need creativity and
we will need cooperation.

00:28:54.200 --> 00:28:58.940
Let me start with
those -- the first one.

00:28:58.940 --> 00:29:01.130
First one is trade.

00:29:01.130 --> 00:29:04.120
I've been saying
for some time now

00:29:04.120 --> 00:29:07.310
that we need to fix the system.

00:29:07.310 --> 00:29:09.070
More recently, I've
been urging countries

00:29:09.070 --> 00:29:11.210
to actually de-escalate
trade [inaudible].

00:29:11.210 --> 00:29:13.450
And it was encouraging to see

00:29:13.450 --> 00:29:16.130
over the weekend
some progress made

00:29:16.130 --> 00:29:19.830
at the G20 meeting
in Buenos Aires.

00:29:19.830 --> 00:29:23.160
And we must continue
the de-escalation while

00:29:23.160 --> 00:29:26.620
at the some time improving the
trading system for the future.

00:29:26.620 --> 00:29:31.280
That would include eliminating
distortionary subsidies,

00:29:31.280 --> 00:29:33.930
whichever form or
color they take,

00:29:33.930 --> 00:29:36.170
but agreeing on what they are.

00:29:36.170 --> 00:29:39.880
It would also mean protecting
intellectual properties rights

00:29:39.880 --> 00:29:46.290
without stifling innovation and
getting rid of economic grants.

00:29:46.290 --> 00:29:49.300
New trade agreements could
unleash the potential

00:29:49.300 --> 00:29:51.980
of e-commerce and
trade in services.

00:29:51.980 --> 00:29:54.160
And all of this is critical.

00:29:54.160 --> 00:29:55.970
Not for the sake of trade,

00:29:55.970 --> 00:29:58.590
although Montesquieu
would argue with me.

00:29:58.590 --> 00:30:03.500
And he would say, where there
is trade there is good manners.

00:30:03.500 --> 00:30:05.860
Is he right?

00:30:05.860 --> 00:30:08.990
Montesquieu is always right.

00:30:08.990 --> 00:30:13.560
No, it's critical because
trade lifts productivity.

00:30:13.560 --> 00:30:16.210
Trade accelerates innovation.

00:30:16.210 --> 00:30:18.810
And we need both.

00:30:18.810 --> 00:30:21.830
Second issue where we
need more cooperation is

00:30:21.830 --> 00:30:24.750
international taxation.

00:30:24.750 --> 00:30:29.030
Companies now have
world-wide presence,

00:30:29.030 --> 00:30:30.330
even when they're small.

00:30:30.330 --> 00:30:32.430
In the old days,
you had to be one

00:30:32.430 --> 00:30:36.520
of those top guns
to be international.

00:30:36.520 --> 00:30:41.080
Now, very small companies can
be very international companies.

00:30:41.080 --> 00:30:46.150
But governments have
not figured, yet,

00:30:46.150 --> 00:30:49.420
a world wide answer to tax.

00:30:49.420 --> 00:30:52.710
And right now, too many
tax dollars are left

00:30:52.710 --> 00:30:56.010
on the table thanks
to tax optimization

00:30:56.010 --> 00:30:59.250
and the bad kind of creativity.

00:30:59.250 --> 00:31:02.710
So countries need to
work closely together

00:31:02.710 --> 00:31:07.030
to collect what is
owed, where it's owed,

00:31:07.030 --> 00:31:10.410
and avoid a race
tax to the bottom.

00:31:10.410 --> 00:31:12.180
They can close the
loopholes that lead

00:31:12.180 --> 00:31:16.250
to what is called base
erosion and profit shifting.

00:31:16.250 --> 00:31:19.010
We are working with our partners

00:31:19.010 --> 00:31:21.520
so that our members can
share best practices

00:31:21.520 --> 00:31:24.450
and devise regulation
for digital economy

00:31:24.450 --> 00:31:29.600
in which many companies have
no single established based

00:31:29.600 --> 00:31:33.720
of operation, and
yet they do operate.

00:31:33.720 --> 00:31:35.850
Why do we need this?

00:31:35.850 --> 00:31:38.000
Why do we need revenue?

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:42.170
Because all countries should
be investing in their future.

00:31:42.170 --> 00:31:45.690
And public and private funding
working together can strengthen

00:31:45.690 --> 00:31:50.180
infrastructure, improve
education, and prepare all of us

00:31:50.180 --> 00:31:52.920
to adjust to the
technical transformations

00:31:52.920 --> 00:31:54.610
of at our doorsteps.

00:31:54.610 --> 00:31:56.810
When the return on
those investments is

00:31:56.810 --> 00:31:59.030
so far away it's very unlikely

00:31:59.030 --> 00:32:03.310
that private sector alone
will actually invest.

00:32:03.310 --> 00:32:05.940
My third issue is our climate.

00:32:05.940 --> 00:32:10.620
From the recent major
hurricanes in the Caribbean

00:32:10.620 --> 00:32:14.360
to the wild fires in California
to the sinking islands

00:32:14.360 --> 00:32:16.900
of the Pacific, the
dangerous effects

00:32:16.900 --> 00:32:21.190
of climate change are becoming
more tangible by the day.

00:32:21.190 --> 00:32:24.600
A new U.S. government study
shows that the economic impact

00:32:24.600 --> 00:32:27.890
from climate change could
significantly reduce America's

00:32:27.890 --> 00:32:30.650
GDP in the coming decades.

00:32:30.650 --> 00:32:33.800
The collaborative
agreement reached in Paris

00:32:33.800 --> 00:32:37.290
in 2015 is probably the
best toolbox that we have

00:32:37.290 --> 00:32:40.070
to start fixing the
planetary challenge

00:32:40.070 --> 00:32:44.180
and move towards
zero carbon economy.

00:32:44.180 --> 00:32:46.510
It also reflects some of
the ideas that I've tried

00:32:46.510 --> 00:32:50.120
to highlight tonight,
creativity, visionary thinking,

00:32:50.120 --> 00:32:52.090
and a global commitment
to the common good

00:32:52.090 --> 00:32:55.410
that serves self interest.

00:32:55.410 --> 00:32:59.100
This is as much of survival
for future generations.

00:32:59.100 --> 00:33:06.810
Now I've mentioned three
issues, trade, tax, and climate.

00:33:06.810 --> 00:33:09.940
And each of them is worthy of
their own Kissinger lecture.

00:33:09.940 --> 00:33:13.710
But there is one issue that
I believe is the bedrock

00:33:13.710 --> 00:33:16.300
for progress nearly
everywhere else.

00:33:16.300 --> 00:33:19.720
And that is why the fourth
and final area I want

00:33:19.720 --> 00:33:22.950
to discuss is good governance,

00:33:22.950 --> 00:33:25.450
free from the shackles
of corruption.

00:33:25.450 --> 00:33:30.810
The simple fact is that without
confidence in our institutions,

00:33:30.810 --> 00:33:33.380
none of the change we
seek will be possible.

00:33:33.380 --> 00:33:34.740
So let me focus on that briefly.

00:33:34.740 --> 00:33:38.130
It's my four and last key point.

00:33:38.130 --> 00:33:41.680
Why is corruption so corrosive?

00:33:41.680 --> 00:33:45.120
Because when people start people
the economy no longer works

00:33:45.120 --> 00:33:48.080
for them, society no
longer works for them,

00:33:48.080 --> 00:33:50.310
they start disconnecting
from economy

00:33:50.310 --> 00:33:53.340
and disconnecting from society.

00:33:53.340 --> 00:33:55.570
Corruption saps economic
vitality

00:33:55.570 --> 00:33:59.050
and siphons off desperately
need resources.

00:33:59.050 --> 00:34:02.710
The money that is diverted
from education and health,

00:34:02.710 --> 00:34:04.360
perpetuates inequality

00:34:04.360 --> 00:34:07.080
and limits the possibility
of a better life.

00:34:07.080 --> 00:34:11.330
Do you know what the annual
cost of bribery alone,

00:34:11.330 --> 00:34:14.350
and corruption is more than
just bribery, but the cost

00:34:14.350 --> 00:34:18.060
of bribery every year is 1.5 --

00:34:18.060 --> 00:34:21.550
is estimated to be
at $1.5 trillion.

00:34:21.550 --> 00:34:24.690
That's roughly 2
percent of global GDP.

00:34:27.390 --> 00:34:30.940
Millennials feel
the problem acutely.

00:34:30.940 --> 00:34:33.110
A recent survey of
global youth revealed

00:34:33.110 --> 00:34:37.790
that young people identify
corruption, not jobs,

00:34:37.790 --> 00:34:40.210
not better education,
but corruption

00:34:40.210 --> 00:34:43.540
as the most pressing concern
in their own countries.

00:34:43.540 --> 00:34:46.140
There is wisdom in this insight.

00:34:46.140 --> 00:34:48.440
Because corruption is
the root cause of many

00:34:48.440 --> 00:34:50.710
of economic injustices that many

00:34:50.710 --> 00:34:53.670
of these young men
and women are facing.

00:34:53.670 --> 00:34:56.900
And that is why,
with the support

00:34:56.900 --> 00:34:59.910
of our entire membership
we are going

00:34:59.910 --> 00:35:02.540
to scrutinize [inaudible]
the impact of corruption

00:35:02.540 --> 00:35:05.330
on a country's macroeconomic
health.

00:35:05.330 --> 00:35:08.720
So far we've done quite a bit
of work on anti-money laundering

00:35:08.720 --> 00:35:10.570
and combating the
financing of terrorism.

00:35:10.570 --> 00:35:11.870
We've done that.

00:35:11.870 --> 00:35:14.260
We had 110 of our
country members.

00:35:14.260 --> 00:35:17.490
But it's only a small part of
the wider work that is needed

00:35:17.490 --> 00:35:19.770
to promote good governance.

00:35:19.770 --> 00:35:22.830
Investing in institution
is indispensable

00:35:22.830 --> 00:35:25.770
as is indispensable
[inaudible] to verify

00:35:25.770 --> 00:35:30.690
that those institutions
actually deliver.

00:35:30.690 --> 00:35:36.030
Because likewise,
corruption knows no border.

00:35:36.030 --> 00:35:40.980
Think for a second, how Phintec
[assumed spelling] is changing

00:35:40.980 --> 00:35:42.900
the economic game.

00:35:42.900 --> 00:35:45.820
New innovations including
cryptocurrencies,

00:35:45.820 --> 00:35:50.110
crypto-assets can be
used by cybercriminals

00:35:50.110 --> 00:35:52.330
to funnel illicit
financial flows

00:35:52.330 --> 00:35:56.930
and fund illegal activities
on a worldwide basis.

00:35:56.930 --> 00:35:58.900
This is not one nation's problem

00:35:58.900 --> 00:36:01.850
or within one nation's
power to resolve.

00:36:01.850 --> 00:36:06.430
It can only be fixed through
cross border collaboration.

00:36:06.430 --> 00:36:08.230
But it is fixable.

00:36:08.230 --> 00:36:09.820
Because the same innovations

00:36:09.820 --> 00:36:13.120
that create cross border
challenges can also be used

00:36:13.120 --> 00:36:17.410
to help us fight back
through biometrics,

00:36:17.410 --> 00:36:19.770
block chain, and more.

00:36:19.770 --> 00:36:22.920
We can find creative
ways to build a better,

00:36:22.920 --> 00:36:26.060
safer system for the long term.

00:36:26.060 --> 00:36:30.640
Governments can and must work
with the world's best engineers

00:36:30.640 --> 00:36:33.290
to build stronger
cybersecurity systems

00:36:33.290 --> 00:36:36.200
that protect people's bank
account, their well being,

00:36:36.200 --> 00:36:38.220
and even their hotel booking.

00:36:38.220 --> 00:36:43.680
This is common good that
we must choose to support.

00:36:43.680 --> 00:36:49.140
And if we take -- if we take
the challenge of corruption

00:36:49.140 --> 00:36:54.100
as the model of cooperation
that we can actually implement,

00:36:54.100 --> 00:36:59.650
it can be a model for the
other topics that I mentioned.

00:36:59.650 --> 00:37:03.340
It can be the sign that
the brotherhood of man,

00:37:03.340 --> 00:37:07.110
as Keynes called it,
is ready once again

00:37:07.110 --> 00:37:08.860
to meet the call of history.

00:37:08.860 --> 00:37:16.510
Except, by the way, that this
time women will play a role.

00:37:16.510 --> 00:37:26.220
[ Applause ]

00:37:26.220 --> 00:37:28.710
You should have seen
the photo of those

00:37:28.710 --> 00:37:32.400
who created Bretton
Woods in 1944.

00:37:32.400 --> 00:37:35.070
Forty-four men.

00:37:35.070 --> 00:37:36.370
Full stop.

00:37:36.370 --> 00:37:39.490
So I think it's by doing

00:37:39.490 --> 00:37:41.580
that that we can
start restoring trust,

00:37:41.580 --> 00:37:43.850
which is probably the
most precious and most

00:37:43.850 --> 00:37:46.770
in demand commodity
in our society.

00:37:46.770 --> 00:37:50.460
And this is how we begin to
adapt once more and reimagine

00:37:50.460 --> 00:37:54.420
that international
cooperation that we need.

00:37:55.460 --> 00:38:00.080
Now before I conclude, we
have one more thing to do.

00:38:00.080 --> 00:38:02.060
I began my remark by mentioning

00:38:02.060 --> 00:38:05.220
that December 4th was
an important date.

00:38:05.220 --> 00:38:06.910
Now, there's one person
who is not allowed

00:38:06.910 --> 00:38:08.760
to answer that question.

00:38:08.760 --> 00:38:12.090
That's Mrs. Harmon,
who is the president

00:38:12.090 --> 00:38:15.750
of the Woodrow Wilson Center.

00:38:15.750 --> 00:38:22.970
Because on December 4,
1918, exactly 100 years ago

00:38:22.970 --> 00:38:27.790
to this day, President Woodrow
Wilson set sail for France

00:38:27.790 --> 00:38:32.110
to help negotiate what he
hoped would be a lasting peace.

00:38:32.110 --> 00:38:33.860
He became the first U.S. --

00:38:33.860 --> 00:38:38.120
the first sitting U.S.
President to travel to Europe.

00:38:38.120 --> 00:38:42.130
And in some way -- some ways,
we can trace the origins

00:38:42.130 --> 00:38:44.870
of modern creativity
and visionary thinking

00:38:44.870 --> 00:38:48.870
in U.S. foreign policy
to this date.

00:38:48.870 --> 00:38:51.590
It's also a humbling reminder

00:38:51.590 --> 00:38:56.240
that our plans do not
always work out as intended.

00:38:56.240 --> 00:39:01.680
But it is also a signal that we
must try and try and try again.

00:39:01.680 --> 00:39:05.410
We must build on what
worked, change what does not,

00:39:05.410 --> 00:39:08.580
and continually evolve, improve,

00:39:08.580 --> 00:39:11.490
imagine a better
future for all people.

00:39:11.490 --> 00:39:15.460
It was the vision that inspired
the leaders of this country

00:39:15.460 --> 00:39:19.380
and it must be the mission that
will guide us in the days ahead.

00:39:19.380 --> 00:39:21.180
Thank you, very much.

00:39:21.180 --> 00:39:39.850
