That's the vision that he
describes the U.S. should be

00:48:24.250 --> 00:48:25.550
implementing right now.

00:48:25.550 --> 00:48:27.260
What do you make
of that proposal?

00:48:27.260 --> 00:48:29.230
Because it was delivered
in Brussels,

00:48:29.230 --> 00:48:32.360
and it ruffled a few feathers.

00:48:32.360 --> 00:48:33.820
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Well,
you know, on the point

00:48:33.820 --> 00:48:38.860
of making sure that
private capital can invest,

00:48:38.860 --> 00:48:40.800
that's exactly what we do.

00:48:40.800 --> 00:48:44.180
It is because private capital
has completely lost interest

00:48:44.180 --> 00:48:45.790
in certain countries.

00:48:45.790 --> 00:48:49.460
You know, when I look at the
three that I've mentioned,

00:48:49.460 --> 00:48:51.440
Egypt, Ukraine, Argentina.

00:48:51.440 --> 00:48:52.910
Why did we come in?

00:48:52.910 --> 00:48:54.540
because nobody else
wanted to come in.

00:48:54.540 --> 00:48:56.780
Because there was not a single
investor who was prepared

00:48:56.780 --> 00:49:00.280
to take the risk of going
in because the situation was

00:49:00.280 --> 00:49:03.050
in disorder, because
public finances were not

00:49:03.050 --> 00:49:04.350
properly managed.

00:49:04.350 --> 00:49:05.650
Because there were
external factors

00:49:05.650 --> 00:49:08.300
that created massive
instability.

00:49:08.300 --> 00:49:11.660
So we come in and we
enable the country

00:49:11.660 --> 00:49:12.980
to become attractive again.

00:49:12.980 --> 00:49:15.760
So it's not as if
we were a substitute

00:49:15.760 --> 00:49:18.910
to private sector
investors -- investment.

00:49:18.910 --> 00:49:21.330
We are the facilitators
of that investment.

00:49:21.330 --> 00:49:23.060
Because otherwise
they won't come.

00:49:23.060 --> 00:49:24.380
They simply won't come.

00:49:24.380 --> 00:49:25.680
Too risky for them.

00:49:25.680 --> 00:49:28.970
Once they know that we are
involved, it means that we put

00:49:28.970 --> 00:49:32.110
in place, you know,
debt sustainability.

00:49:32.110 --> 00:49:35.820
If restructuring is
needed, we ask for it.

00:49:35.820 --> 00:49:41.260
If new monetary policy needs to
be implemented, we recommend it

00:49:41.260 --> 00:49:46.580
and it's implemented, with
some success, I dare say.

00:49:46.580 --> 00:49:52.130
So I'm not sure that he
understands very clearly what is

00:49:52.130 --> 00:49:54.490
-- well, our mission
is prosperity.

00:49:54.490 --> 00:49:59.520
And yes, this is what the
initial founders actually tasked

00:49:59.520 --> 00:50:02.010
us to do and that's
what we need to do.

00:50:02.010 --> 00:50:03.750
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: So these
descriptions of the vision

00:50:03.750 --> 00:50:07.670
and the leadership that
America's providing

00:50:07.670 --> 00:50:12.600
on this front, for you it is not
achieving what you were saying

00:50:12.600 --> 00:50:16.130
is needed to meet the crisis,
right now, that you see.

00:50:16.130 --> 00:50:17.900
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde:
I was curious

00:50:17.900 --> 00:50:19.200
about the taxpayers' money.

00:50:19.200 --> 00:50:21.200
Because you know, the --

00:50:21.200 --> 00:50:25.380
we've actually always
paid back and more.

00:50:25.380 --> 00:50:26.690
So over the course of time,

00:50:26.690 --> 00:50:29.460
the United States has actually
made quite a bit of money

00:50:29.460 --> 00:50:33.120
out of the IMF involvement
in countries.

00:50:33.120 --> 00:50:34.500
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: You think
there's just a fundamental

00:50:34.500 --> 00:50:37.260
misunderstanding or
are there portions

00:50:37.260 --> 00:50:39.700
of truth to these criticisms?

00:50:39.700 --> 00:50:41.000
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Well,

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:45.110
the fact that growth must
be generated as a result

00:50:45.110 --> 00:50:48.440
of our involvement is something
that I completely agree with.

00:50:48.440 --> 00:50:49.900
It doesn't come overnight.

00:50:49.900 --> 00:50:52.710
Because you need to, you
know, restore the situation.

00:50:52.710 --> 00:50:55.170
You need to sort
out public finance.

00:50:55.170 --> 00:50:58.150
You need to reorganize
sometimes, you know,

00:50:58.150 --> 00:51:00.700
through structural
reforms, the economy.

00:51:00.700 --> 00:51:02.910
But growth ultimately
comes back.

00:51:02.910 --> 00:51:06.530
When I look at -- I'll tell
you, as French finance minister,

00:51:06.530 --> 00:51:09.890
we had to deal with some
difficult cases in Europe.

00:51:09.890 --> 00:51:13.290
But when I look at a country
like Portugal, the involvement

00:51:13.290 --> 00:51:16.670
of the IMF was critical in
turning the situation around

00:51:16.670 --> 00:51:19.550
and sorting out quite
a few difficult issues.

00:51:19.550 --> 00:51:21.920
Portugal is now doing
pretty well compared

00:51:21.920 --> 00:51:23.510
with other European countries.

00:51:23.510 --> 00:51:27.490
When I look at Ireland,
Ireland is thriving.

00:51:27.490 --> 00:51:29.100
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: These
are countries that needed --

00:51:29.100 --> 00:51:31.670
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Those are
countries where we had to come

00:51:31.670 --> 00:51:33.770
in as the IMF, we had to put

00:51:33.770 --> 00:51:36.530
in place significant
lending programs.

00:51:36.530 --> 00:51:40.190
And we expected serious
measures to be taken

00:51:40.190 --> 00:51:42.630
on the physical front, because
there was too much fiscal

00:51:42.630 --> 00:51:46.590
deficit, and because the
-- in the case of Ireland,

00:51:46.590 --> 00:51:49.620
because the banking system
was completely out of control

00:51:49.620 --> 00:51:53.200
and had gone way too far into
expanding beyond the country.

00:51:53.200 --> 00:51:59.620
So you know, these programs
have clearly generated a growth.

00:51:59.620 --> 00:52:02.280
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: When you
use that phrase, you know,

00:52:02.280 --> 00:52:05.040
describing, we could
live in an age of anger.

00:52:05.040 --> 00:52:08.910
You're putting a timeline
out, decades from now.

00:52:08.910 --> 00:52:11.670
If you look at some
of the forces,

00:52:11.670 --> 00:52:14.610
not just in the United
States, that contributed

00:52:14.610 --> 00:52:17.020
to making trade a very
contentious issue during the

00:52:17.020 --> 00:52:20.180
2016 campaign, on the
left and on the right,

00:52:20.180 --> 00:52:21.960
but also what you're
seeing in Europe,

00:52:21.960 --> 00:52:23.590
in your home country
of France right now.

00:52:23.590 --> 00:52:28.940
Protests around the economy
and specifically the gas tax.

00:52:28.940 --> 00:52:32.530
I won't get into President
Trump's tweet about it tonight.

00:52:32.530 --> 00:52:35.090
But generally speaking,

00:52:35.090 --> 00:52:38.150
aren't you seeing
those forces of anger.

00:52:38.150 --> 00:52:40.510
I mean, you're seeing more
populace governments come

00:52:40.510 --> 00:52:45.390
to power or at least use the
economy and anti-insti --

00:52:45.390 --> 00:52:48.730
anti-multilateral
institutional rhetoric

00:52:48.730 --> 00:52:50.870
in a lot of places right now.

00:52:50.870 --> 00:52:52.170
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Yes.

00:52:52.170 --> 00:52:53.470
That is --

00:52:53.470 --> 00:52:54.770
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: Are we in
that age that you're describing?

00:52:54.770 --> 00:52:56.070
I mean, where are
we as the time --

00:52:56.070 --> 00:52:58.220
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: We
are at risk of slipping

00:52:58.220 --> 00:53:02.200
into that kind of age of anger.

00:53:02.200 --> 00:53:04.030
Which is why it is
critically important

00:53:04.030 --> 00:53:06.060
to actually address
those issues.

00:53:06.060 --> 00:53:11.290
As I was trying to explain in
my remarks, those are not issues

00:53:11.290 --> 00:53:14.710
that can be addressed
purely domestically.

00:53:14.710 --> 00:53:17.860
Some of them have to be
addressed domestically.

00:53:17.860 --> 00:53:21.700
But when it comes to trade,
to tax, to climate change,

00:53:21.700 --> 00:53:25.940
to cybersecurity, to
corruption it has to be

00:53:25.940 --> 00:53:29.510
on an international
cooperation basis, as well.

00:53:29.510 --> 00:53:32.230
They come together.

00:53:32.230 --> 00:53:35.630
But, yes, there has to be
a response to those issues

00:53:35.630 --> 00:53:40.590
because many people are not
satisfied with their income,

00:53:40.590 --> 00:53:43.840
are not satisfied with their
future, have this anxiety

00:53:43.840 --> 00:53:48.130
of what the future holds
for their children and it --

00:53:48.130 --> 00:53:51.090
all these concerns
need to be addressed.

00:53:51.090 --> 00:53:55.540
Need to be addressed
by societies at large.

00:53:55.540 --> 00:53:57.210
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: The
challenge there is that lack

00:53:57.210 --> 00:54:00.750
of trust in the institutions
that are tasked with this

00:54:00.750 --> 00:54:03.270
or have been tasked with this.

00:54:03.270 --> 00:54:04.570
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Yes.

00:54:04.570 --> 00:54:05.870
Yes.

00:54:05.870 --> 00:54:07.170
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan:
You mentioned your time

00:54:07.170 --> 00:54:08.470
when you were Minister
of Finance in France,

00:54:08.470 --> 00:54:10.770
and clearly one of the most
difficult time periods you could

00:54:10.770 --> 00:54:12.070
have that job.

00:54:12.070 --> 00:54:15.930
And I remember from covering
it, that famous story

00:54:15.930 --> 00:54:19.570
of you speaking to then
Treasury Secretary Hank Paulson

00:54:19.570 --> 00:54:22.470
and advising him against
allowing Lehman Brothers

00:54:22.470 --> 00:54:23.770
to go under.

00:54:23.770 --> 00:54:25.070
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Yes.

00:54:25.070 --> 00:54:27.450
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: You
foresaw the domino affect.

00:54:28.490 --> 00:54:31.440
Did you see -- did
you draw a line

00:54:31.440 --> 00:54:35.910
between what you predicted
then and where we are now?

00:54:35.910 --> 00:54:39.940
Is that where this shift
began, that you're laying out?

00:54:41.010 --> 00:54:42.310
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde:

00:54:42.310 --> 00:54:44.520
I certainly did not
anticipate that at the time.

00:54:44.520 --> 00:54:47.280
But looking back, yes, I
think that there is a lot

00:54:47.280 --> 00:54:49.380
in today's anger, resentment,

00:54:49.380 --> 00:54:53.230
frustration that is
actually attributable

00:54:53.230 --> 00:54:55.270
to the legacy of the crisis.

00:54:55.270 --> 00:54:59.860
I think that we did a
reasonably good job in trying

00:54:59.860 --> 00:55:01.780
to strengthen the
financial system,

00:55:01.780 --> 00:55:05.800
avoid that people actually
lose all their savings,

00:55:05.800 --> 00:55:09.610
and that there be bank runs
all over those countries.

00:55:09.610 --> 00:55:15.040
But, I think, the fact that
we addressed the issues

00:55:15.040 --> 00:55:18.560
of institutions, of the
financial system at large,

00:55:18.560 --> 00:55:20.780
without doing probably
enough explanation

00:55:20.780 --> 00:55:22.850
as what it meant for people.

00:55:22.850 --> 00:55:28.300
And the fact that many involved

00:55:28.300 --> 00:55:36.800
in those financial deals
got away with it and managed

00:55:36.800 --> 00:55:39.000
to reestablish themselves,
I think,

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:42.120
created a sense of impunity.

00:55:42.120 --> 00:55:43.600
In other words, some
of the lower,

00:55:43.600 --> 00:55:45.970
middle class people
thinking to themselves, okay,

00:55:45.970 --> 00:55:47.790
I've lost my job,
I've lost my house.

00:55:47.790 --> 00:55:51.310
And those people,
what have they lost?

00:55:51.310 --> 00:55:52.610
Their bonus?

00:55:52.610 --> 00:55:53.990
Yes. But that's about it.

00:55:53.990 --> 00:55:56.300
And they reestablished
themselves.

00:55:56.300 --> 00:56:02.060
So I think this is not at the
root of and the only component

00:56:02.060 --> 00:56:05.710
of the frustration and
the anger that we see,

00:56:05.710 --> 00:56:08.970
but it certainly
participates and fueling it.

00:56:10.230 --> 00:56:11.530
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: So how --

00:56:11.530 --> 00:56:12.830
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde:
That's what I call the sort

00:56:12.830 --> 00:56:15.050
of untold story of the
legacy of the crisis.

00:56:15.050 --> 00:56:18.410
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: So how
do you address that then?

00:56:18.410 --> 00:56:21.340
If that age of anger
is simmering.

00:56:21.340 --> 00:56:22.640
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde:
I think it's, you know,

00:56:22.640 --> 00:56:24.710
in a way it's too late
to go back to things

00:56:24.710 --> 00:56:27.440
that should have taken
place at that time.

00:56:27.440 --> 00:56:31.860
But we also have the possibility
with new technologies,

00:56:31.860 --> 00:56:35.270
a digital age, that is clearly
in the making at the moment

00:56:35.270 --> 00:56:40.060
and at an accelerated pace,
to organize it in such a way

00:56:40.060 --> 00:56:43.020
that it is transparent,
that it is accountable,

00:56:43.020 --> 00:56:46.210
that it includes people,
that they are brought in to

00:56:46.210 --> 00:56:50.530
that digital picture by being
properly trained, educated,

00:56:50.530 --> 00:56:55.060
skilled and that they don't
feel there's emasculation

00:56:55.060 --> 00:56:59.180
that you have when something is
so alien to you, and so foreign

00:56:59.180 --> 00:57:04.910
to you that yet again you
feel that anger about it.

00:57:04.910 --> 00:57:06.800
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: You
want another Bretton Woods

00:57:06.800 --> 00:57:09.320
type summit?

00:57:09.320 --> 00:57:10.910
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: There's so
many groups that are thinking,

00:57:10.910 --> 00:57:12.700
oh, let's have another
Bretton Woods.

00:57:12.700 --> 00:57:14.570
Let's just reform.

00:57:14.570 --> 00:57:15.870
I think it's --

00:57:15.870 --> 00:57:17.520
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan:
Who leads this?

00:57:17.520 --> 00:57:19.100
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Oh, there
are multiple leaders everywhere.

00:57:19.100 --> 00:57:22.530
You know. They don't have
to do the job of, you know,

00:57:22.530 --> 00:57:26.470
giving advice, drafting and
preparing those programs,

00:57:26.470 --> 00:57:29.010
and providing technical
assistance around the globe

00:57:29.010 --> 00:57:31.470
to have an 89 countries.

00:57:31.470 --> 00:57:35.370
But the beauty of
the institution

00:57:35.370 --> 00:57:40.680
that I have the privilege to
lead, is that in its articles,

00:57:40.680 --> 00:57:44.170
in its foundations,
are the seeds

00:57:44.170 --> 00:57:46.640
for constant transformation.

00:57:46.640 --> 00:57:51.340
What is changing
massively around it calls

00:57:51.340 --> 00:57:54.390
for probably a different
approach.

00:57:54.390 --> 00:57:58.650
I think, that the digital
economy in which we are moving,

00:57:58.650 --> 00:58:00.770
which is transforming
the financial sector,

00:58:00.770 --> 00:58:06.690
which is transforming
the existing relationship

00:58:06.690 --> 00:58:14.180
between value and monetary cost,
all that needs new thinking.

00:58:14.180 --> 00:58:16.700
I think it's more new
thinking than a reform

00:58:16.700 --> 00:58:19.420
of the Bretton Woods system.

00:58:19.420 --> 00:58:21.520
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: I know
the IMF has written on this

00:58:21.520 --> 00:58:25.980
and talked about demand for
cash decreasing and, you know,

00:58:25.980 --> 00:58:28.120
money itself is changing,

00:58:28.120 --> 00:58:30.790
not just how we think
and talk about this.

00:58:30.790 --> 00:58:34.400
You mentioned Phintec in that
context, financial technologies

00:58:34.400 --> 00:58:37.330
and all the various forms of it.

00:58:37.330 --> 00:58:41.450
I mean, where there
are advantages

00:58:41.450 --> 00:58:44.260
and there are disadvantages,
these days it seems

00:58:44.260 --> 00:58:49.700
to be not very well understood,
even by the public at large.

00:58:49.700 --> 00:58:53.180
How much more of this needs
to be led, not by the IMF

00:58:53.180 --> 00:58:55.930
or these organizations, but
coming from the corporate world?

00:58:55.930 --> 00:58:58.180
Coming from Silicon Valley?

00:58:58.180 --> 00:59:00.880
You have these hearings on
Capital Hill and the joke is,

00:59:00.880 --> 00:59:04.100
you know, you have these CEOs
come up and answer questions

00:59:04.100 --> 00:59:06.910
and the individuals asking
them don't even know how

00:59:06.910 --> 00:59:09.780
to use the websites that
they're talking about.

00:59:09.780 --> 00:59:13.990
You know, I mean, how do you
regulate cryptocurrencies?

00:59:13.990 --> 00:59:16.510
How do you talk about
all of this in a way

00:59:16.510 --> 00:59:20.590
that actually leads to some
kind of regulation or reform?

00:59:21.750 --> 00:59:23.050
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde:
Well, first of all,

00:59:23.050 --> 00:59:24.680
I don't think it should be
entirely left in the hands

00:59:24.680 --> 00:59:28.710
of those corporate
sector representatives

00:59:28.710 --> 00:59:32.590
or their legal departments
or their public affairs.

00:59:32.590 --> 00:59:35.700
Because they are dealing
with a common good.

00:59:35.700 --> 00:59:37.260
They're dealing with
your privacy.

00:59:37.260 --> 00:59:38.990
They're dealing with your data.

00:59:38.990 --> 00:59:41.660
And they're dealing
with your freedom.

00:59:41.660 --> 00:59:43.960
So --

00:59:46.190 --> 00:59:48.630
So governmental authorities,

00:59:48.630 --> 00:59:50.790
Parliamentarians
have to be involved.

00:59:50.790 --> 00:59:53.850
And they have to be held
along the way for those

00:59:53.850 --> 00:59:55.440
who are not computer literate,

00:59:55.440 --> 00:59:57.450
for those who feel
completely alien

00:59:57.450 --> 00:59:59.980
to this digital transformation.

00:59:59.980 --> 01:00:02.910
They have to be held by --
including my people like us,

01:00:02.910 --> 01:00:06.390
the IMF, in relation to
financial technologies.

01:00:06.390 --> 01:00:12.010
Because, you know, we try
to grasp what it means,

01:00:12.010 --> 01:00:15.000
how its formed, how those
technologies are used

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:19.830
to shorten the circuits
to enable payments

01:00:19.830 --> 01:00:22.810
and to include people that
we're not including --

01:00:22.810 --> 01:00:26.520
not included in the banking
sector, for instance.

01:00:26.520 --> 01:00:31.050
So it is a public
responsibility.

01:00:31.050 --> 01:00:34.200
And it has to be done, again, in
cooperation with those engineers

01:00:34.200 --> 01:00:37.010
and in cooperation with those
who understand the future

01:00:37.010 --> 01:00:40.150
of data protection, who
understands, you know,

01:00:40.150 --> 01:00:44.060
how cloud will eventually
be accessible

01:00:44.060 --> 01:00:47.100
or be raidable and hackable.

01:00:47.100 --> 01:00:50.370
So there are many technicalities
that you don't master,

01:00:50.370 --> 01:00:52.320
that I don't master either.

01:00:52.320 --> 01:00:53.970
But, you know, having
enough knowledge

01:00:53.970 --> 01:00:56.690
to understand the key
principles that need

01:00:56.690 --> 01:01:01.120
to be respected is something, I
believe, fall on the shoulders

01:01:01.120 --> 01:01:04.990
of Parliamentarians and
members of government

01:01:04.990 --> 01:01:07.630
because they today
have the responsibility

01:01:07.630 --> 01:01:10.140
to represent the people.

01:01:10.140 --> 01:01:11.930
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: You've
also issued a number of calls

01:01:11.930 --> 01:01:14.080
for some of those
parliamentarians to get rid

01:01:14.080 --> 01:01:16.780
of the legal obstacles
to inclusion of women.

01:01:16.780 --> 01:01:18.080
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Yes.

01:01:18.080 --> 01:01:19.380
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan:
In the economy.

01:01:19.380 --> 01:01:20.680
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Yes.

01:01:20.680 --> 01:01:21.980
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan:
Where does that begin?

01:01:21.980 --> 01:01:23.280
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: It
very often begins at home.

01:01:23.280 --> 01:01:27.440
Of the 189 countries that are
members of the institution,

01:01:27.440 --> 01:01:31.390
about 90 percent still
have in their constitution

01:01:31.390 --> 01:01:35.730
or in the legal system
discrimination against women,

01:01:35.730 --> 01:01:44.610
barriers to the participation in
the economy, to the inheritance

01:01:44.610 --> 01:01:50.790
when parents die, to
the owning a business

01:01:50.790 --> 01:01:54.400
to the opening bank account,
to be able to bring collateral

01:01:54.400 --> 01:01:56.590
when they try to have a loan.

01:01:56.590 --> 01:01:59.650
So I think that's where
the work has to begin.

01:01:59.650 --> 01:02:02.070
And we have demonstrated
in many countries,

01:02:02.070 --> 01:02:04.470
or observed in many
countries such as, you know,

01:02:04.470 --> 01:02:06.830
some Latin American
countries like Peru,

01:02:06.830 --> 01:02:08.740
some African countries, as well.

01:02:08.740 --> 01:02:12.990
That when those changes happen,
it actually has consequences

01:02:12.990 --> 01:02:17.930
on the economy and it pushes
growth and it enables women

01:02:17.930 --> 01:02:23.190
to become better
integrated into the economy.

01:02:23.190 --> 01:02:24.610
But it's not only that.

01:02:24.610 --> 01:02:27.540
It begins there because there
should not be legal barriers

01:02:27.540 --> 01:02:33.660
and legal constraints imposed by
governments that prevent women

01:02:33.660 --> 01:02:35.950
from playing their
role in the economy.

01:02:35.950 --> 01:02:38.100
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: How much
of an economic benefit is there?

01:02:38.100 --> 01:02:39.400
How do you quantify --

01:02:39.400 --> 01:02:40.700
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Huge.

01:02:40.700 --> 01:02:42.000
It's huge.

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:43.300
I mean, it varies
from, you know,

01:02:43.300 --> 01:02:44.600
if you look at the
Nordic countries.

01:02:44.600 --> 01:02:49.180
You know, Norway being clearly
one of the best performers.

01:02:49.180 --> 01:02:51.100
Finland being very
good, as well.

01:02:51.100 --> 01:02:56.170
But from those countries to
say, India, Saudi Arabia,

01:02:56.170 --> 01:02:59.140
you can have an increase in
the economy, which varies

01:02:59.140 --> 01:03:01.760
from 3 percent to 27 percent.

01:03:01.760 --> 01:03:03.380
So that's nothing
to be, you know,

01:03:03.380 --> 01:03:05.500
sort of turning your eyes away.

01:03:05.500 --> 01:03:07.920
It's pretty big.

01:03:07.920 --> 01:03:09.470
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan:
Why the resistance?

01:03:09.470 --> 01:03:10.770
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Ha.

01:03:10.770 --> 01:03:12.070
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: If you can
make the argument on numbers,

01:03:12.070 --> 01:03:13.590
why is there is such resistance?

01:03:13.590 --> 01:03:14.900
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: I think
you're talking about something

01:03:14.900 --> 01:03:20.530
that goes much, much deeper
into culture, into psyche,

01:03:20.530 --> 01:03:26.100
into the way in which
societies have been built

01:03:26.100 --> 01:03:27.400
over the course of time.

01:03:27.400 --> 01:03:28.700
You're also talking
about the divide

01:03:28.700 --> 01:03:31.790
between urban centers
and rural areas.

01:03:31.790 --> 01:03:36.190
You know, India is a case
in point, where clearly

01:03:36.190 --> 01:03:40.950
in rural areas, in
particular, women are prevented

01:03:40.950 --> 01:03:46.110
from joining the flow from being
economic partners and sometimes

01:03:46.110 --> 01:03:49.220
from having access
to sanitation.

01:03:49.220 --> 01:03:51.550
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan:
Bigger picture.

01:03:51.550 --> 01:03:53.610
I know we're running
out of time here.

01:03:53.610 --> 01:03:56.710
I would be remis if I
didn't ask you about Brexit.

01:03:56.710 --> 01:04:02.340
And what this -- we're talking
about the forces sort of pulling

01:04:02.340 --> 01:04:03.870
at the global order right now.

01:04:03.870 --> 01:04:06.440
It's -- that's a rejection

01:04:06.440 --> 01:04:12.900
of international organizations
and solidarity there.

01:04:12.900 --> 01:04:16.820
Add that in to what you're
seeing here in the U.S. as well,

01:04:16.820 --> 01:04:18.330
in terms of that
kind of rejection.

01:04:18.330 --> 01:04:22.220
I mean, it sounds like you're
trying to swim upstream.

01:04:22.220 --> 01:04:23.520
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde:
You know, first of all,

01:04:23.520 --> 01:04:26.270
I think that the situation
has changed and is changing

01:04:26.270 --> 01:04:30.540
in the U.K. When I look at the
latest polls that was produced,

01:04:30.540 --> 01:04:36.050
the shift is now into a
majority of those polled.

01:04:36.050 --> 01:04:40.030
Now, you can turn surveys and
polls whichever way you want.

01:04:40.030 --> 01:04:44.320
But it seems that
there are more Brits

01:04:44.320 --> 01:04:47.490
who would rather
remain than exit.

01:04:47.490 --> 01:04:49.500
Sad. Number one.

01:04:49.500 --> 01:04:53.740
Number two, I think a lot of
the campaign that took place

01:04:53.740 --> 01:04:59.830
at the time, two years ago
now, was geared towards,

01:04:59.830 --> 01:05:03.270
watch out the foreigners
are going to take, you know,

01:05:03.270 --> 01:05:08.020
your meal away and
they're going to have --

01:05:08.020 --> 01:05:11.040
they're going to go first
in the health benefits

01:05:11.040 --> 01:05:12.820
and healthcare system.

01:05:12.820 --> 01:05:15.100
And they're going to take jobs.

01:05:15.100 --> 01:05:19.660
And it was the fear
of the foreigners.

01:05:19.660 --> 01:05:22.310
And fortunately,
from within Europe.

01:05:22.310 --> 01:05:26.660
And it was directed at people
from Poland, from Bulgaria,

01:05:26.660 --> 01:05:29.320
from Romania, who by the way,

01:05:29.320 --> 01:05:31.830
have been extremely
well integrated

01:05:31.830 --> 01:05:36.410
in say the German economy,
as was demonstrated recently,

01:05:36.410 --> 01:05:39.450
in a country that needed
additional skilled labor.

01:05:39.450 --> 01:05:44.720
So that fear factor that was
raised during the campaign may

01:05:44.720 --> 01:05:49.280
have completely missed
the opportunity

01:05:49.280 --> 01:05:53.430
that that particular flow of
migration actually produced

01:05:53.430 --> 01:05:55.690
in an economy next
door, which was Germany.

01:05:55.690 --> 01:05:57.530
So that's a little
bit beside the point.

01:05:57.530 --> 01:05:59.830
But --

01:06:03.420 --> 01:06:08.270
I think there is regret in
many, many European corners.

01:06:08.270 --> 01:06:10.740
I think there is more
regret in the U.K

01:06:10.740 --> 01:06:13.910
than there was only
six months ago.

01:06:13.910 --> 01:06:16.590
And I think there is
now, the realization

01:06:16.590 --> 01:06:22.430
that there will be more
loss as a result of Brexit

01:06:22.430 --> 01:06:26.710
than was ever mentioned,
described, accounted for,

01:06:26.710 --> 01:06:29.160
by those who campaigned
for the Brexit.

01:06:29.160 --> 01:06:34.120
I can say that with
relative confidence

01:06:34.120 --> 01:06:37.070
because when we produced the
article for, for the U.K.,

01:06:37.070 --> 01:06:40.730
which is the annual audit
that we do of all economies,

01:06:40.730 --> 01:06:46.650
we did actually gave -- we did
give at the time three scenarios

01:06:46.650 --> 01:06:50.570
of Brexit, one of which was the
baseline, which was pretty much

01:06:50.570 --> 01:06:53.070
in line with what
everybody assumed.

01:06:53.070 --> 01:06:54.970
But another one which was
a [inaudible] scenario

01:06:54.970 --> 01:06:57.170
which is very close
to some of the numbers

01:06:57.170 --> 01:06:58.600
that we are seeing now.

01:06:58.600 --> 01:07:00.300
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan:
The dark scenario?

01:07:00.300 --> 01:07:02.040
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: In
terms of forecast coming up.

01:07:02.040 --> 01:07:08.090
In case of a Brexit development
and in case of a no-deal Brexit,

01:07:08.090 --> 01:07:11.300
which is what we had considered.

01:07:11.300 --> 01:07:14.600
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: Is that
a warning to brace ourselves?

01:07:14.600 --> 01:07:17.170
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: I think
it was a very clear, you know,

01:07:17.170 --> 01:07:19.860
assessment of what the
consequences would be

01:07:19.860 --> 01:07:24.950
as a result of a no-deal Brexit
scenario, where the terms

01:07:24.950 --> 01:07:28.800
of trade between the U.K.
and its main economic

01:07:28.800 --> 01:07:32.730
and trade partner, which is the
European Union would be done

01:07:32.730 --> 01:07:37.230
under the WTO rules with
no additional sweetener

01:07:37.230 --> 01:07:40.000
to WTO rules.

01:07:40.000 --> 01:07:41.300
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: Wow.

01:07:41.300 --> 01:07:43.590
The dark scenario, is a
scary phrase to end on.

01:07:43.590 --> 01:07:45.490
But, unfortunately,
I'm told that we are --

01:07:45.490 --> 01:07:46.790
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Oh, no.

01:07:46.790 --> 01:07:48.100
But you know there was something
very interesting today,

01:07:48.100 --> 01:07:50.770
which is the attorney
general opinion delivered

01:07:50.770 --> 01:07:52.640
to the European Court
of Justice.

01:07:52.640 --> 01:07:55.550
So for those like me who would
very much like to keep the U.K.

01:07:55.550 --> 01:08:00.030
within the European Union,
there is apparently a perfectly,

01:08:00.030 --> 01:08:03.180
legally acceptable way
to revoke the article 50,

01:08:03.180 --> 01:08:07.530
which is the provision under
which the U.K. pulled out.

01:08:07.530 --> 01:08:09.590
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: You think
that's a viable scenario?

01:08:09.590 --> 01:08:10.890
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: It's
-- at least it's legal.

01:08:10.890 --> 01:08:12.380
I'm a reformed lawyer.

01:08:12.380 --> 01:08:14.560
[ Laughter ]

01:08:14.560 --> 01:08:15.940
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: I
think this is the optimist

01:08:15.940 --> 01:08:17.370
that you described yourself as.

01:08:17.370 --> 01:08:18.670
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Yes, yes.

01:08:18.670 --> 01:08:19.970
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan: Thank
you so much, Madame Lagarde.

01:08:19.970 --> 01:08:21.270
&gt;&gt; Christine Lagarde: Thank you.

01:08:21.270 --> 01:08:23.070
&gt;&gt; Margaret Brennan:
Thanks all of you.

01:08:23.070 --> 01:08:26.170
[ Applause ]

